Target-seq analysis - Patient IF137

Summary of genotyping

Matthieu Duchmann

2020-11-08

Determining the mutationnal status for cDNA and gDNA

This notebook describes the steps from cDNA and gDNA vcfs to cell genotype annotation.

gDNA genotyping

Choice of cut-off

There is a risk of contamination accross the wells. We have to determine a cut-off for read number and vaf to consider a mutation. We look at the distribution of vaf for the different mutations. We chose a cut-off of 30 reads of depth for status assessment, and the given status must be supported by at least 10 reads and a vaf > 2 %. In the publicationn thresholds for the detection of each amplicon were set based on non-template controls and thresholds for mutation calling were based on WT controls and customized for each amplicon (1.5%–4% of the reads). Here the threshold as been set visualy at 2%.

gDNA_data <- data.frame(data.frame(gDNA_vcf@fix), data.frame(gDNA_vcf@gt))
gDNA_data <- gDNA_data %>% 
            filter (POS %in% c(5073770,43094667,105237256,32435438,32435400)) %>%
            mutate (MUT = ifelse (POS == 5073770, "JAK2_V617F",
                          ifelse (POS == 43094667, "U2AF1_Q157R",
                          ifelse (POS == 105237256, "TET2_I1105M",
                          ifelse (POS == 32435438, "ASXL1_Q910A",
                          ifelse (POS == 32435400, "ASXL1_W898R", NA)))))) %>%
            select (-c("CHROM", "POS", "REF", "ALT", "INFO", "ID", "QUAL","FILTER", "FORMAT")) %>%
            pivot_longer(
                  cols = starts_with("Sample"),
                  names_to = "cell_ID",
                  values_to = "genotype",
                  values_drop_na = TRUE) %>%
            separate (genotype, c("GT","GQ","SDP","DP","RD","AD","FREQ","PVAL","RBQ","ABQ","RDF","RDR","ADF","ADR"), ":") %>%
               mutate (AD = as.numeric (AD),
                       RD = as.numeric (RD), 
                       DP = as.numeric(DP),
                       vaf = AD/(AD+RD))


seuil_mut <- 0.015

gDNA_data %>% 
        filter (as.numeric(SDP) > 30) %>%
        ggplot(aes(x = vaf + 0.001, fill = MUT)) + 
        geom_histogram(position="identity", color = "black", alpha=0.5, bins = 50) + 
        scale_x_continuous(trans='log10') + 
        theme_classic() +
        geom_vline(xintercept = seuil_mut, color = "red", size=1.5) +
        xlab("MUT allele frequency") + ylab("Cell count")

gDNA_data %>%
        filter ( as.numeric (SDP) > 30) %>%
        ggplot(aes(x = 1-vaf + 0.001, fill = MUT)) + 
        geom_histogram(position="identity", color = "black", alpha=0.5, bins = 50) + 
        theme_classic() +
        scale_x_continuous(trans='log10') + 
        geom_vline(xintercept = seuil_mut, color = "red", size=1.5) +

Summary for single-cells

  gDNA_data <- gDNA_data %>%
      mutate (status = ifelse (is.na(SDP) | (as.numeric(SDP) < 31), 3,
                       ifelse (RD > 10 & vaf < seuil_mut, 0,
                       ifelse (AD < 10 & vaf > seuil_mut, 0,
                       ifelse (AD > 10 & RD > 10 &  vaf < (1 - seuil_mut) & vaf > seuil_mut, 1,
                       ifelse (AD > 10 & vaf > (1 - seuil_mut), 2,
                       ifelse (RD < 10 & vaf < (1 - seuil_mut), 2, 3)))))))
                        
summary_gDNA <- gDNA_data %>%
  select (MUT, cell_ID, status) %>%
  pivot_wider (names_from = MUT, values_from = status) %>%
  mutate (cell_ID = cell_id)

cDNA genotyping

Choice of cut-off

There is a risk of contamination accross the wells and of PCR errors. We have to determine a cut-off for read number and vaf to consider a mutation. We look at the distribution of vaf for the different mutations. We chose a cut-off of 30 reads of depth for status assessment, and the given status must be supported by at least 10 reads and a vaf > 2 %. The separation is less clear because of potential allelic bias, so we took basically the same threshold as gDNA amplicons.

Clonal identity assignation

Clonal architecture inference using inf SCITE

We used infiny-SCITE (Kuipers, J., Jahn, K., Raphael, B. J., & Beerenwinkel, N. (2017). Single-cell sequencing data reveal widespread recurrence and loss of mutational hits in the life histories of tumors. Genome research, 27(11), 1885-1894.)

Given the noisy mutation profiles of single cells, ∞SCITE performs a stochastic search to find the Maximum Likelihood (ML) or Maximum aposterori (MAP) tree and/or to sample from the posterior probability distribution. Tree reconstruction can be combined with an estimation of the error and doublet rates in the mutation profiles.


./infSCITE -i summary_SCITEIF0137def.tsv -n 5 -m 617 -r 1 -l 900000 -fd 0.001 -ad 0.01 0.01 -cc 0 -names IF0137.geneNames

Only one tree was retained, very similar to what the authors obtained (inf-SCITE do not represent homozyguous mutations)

xtab <- table(published_clone$clone, published_clone$published_genotype)
diagonal.counts <- diag(xtab)
N <- sum(xtab)
row.marginal.props <- rowSums(xtab)/N
col.marginal.props <- colSums(xtab)/N
# Calculer kappa (k)
Po <- sum(diagonal.counts)/N
Pe <- sum(row.marginal.props*col.marginal.props)
k <- (Po - Pe)/(1 - Pe)
